<br>
Interesting buff. It's a nice one, and so far I haven't run into any serious problems using it solo. I've been kiting with it a couple times, and I haven't hit it yet.<br>
The wandering issue is another thing. I have no problems with it wandering as long as MoBs don't aggro from the other side of the zone when it flies by them.<br>
Not being able to use Invisibility and the Familiar is a drawback. The fact that casting the Familiar would make you think that it too could see invis, but apparently not. Casting invis (or hiding for you Dark Elves) will usually cost you two bubs of mana and your familiar. Sometimes it seems to almost kill you.<br>
The size is ok, but I do wish it was smaller. I have problems targeting MoBs when it's standing in front of me. Also when looting, I end up considering it. Kind of annoying, but I can live with it.<br>
The PvP aspects of the Familiar make me cringe. It can not only be killed by other players, but they can do it while it's wandering and ruin your gameplay. They can also use it as a tactic. You summon a familiar, It wanders off, they kill it. They repeat killing it until you start to med, then jump you. One fix would be marking them as untargetable, but then we'd lose their buffs. My idea would be to give the familiars their own buffs. That would save us the hassle of casting buffs on a <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> pet</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> we really didn't want.<br>
Another fix for this would be flagging familiars as level 1 players. That would basically take them out of PvP completely.<br>
I haven't tested dispelling them yet. I plan to soon, but if they can be dispelled, and that causes them to drop your mana, it'll be yet another PvP problem.<br>
<br>
Overall, I give Familiars a C+. If they fix the invis and aggro, it'll get bumped up to a B.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Elnerick's Entombment of Ice</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
I've only toyed around with this, and haven't really used it in groups yet. It seems to have the same problem as our stuns; if the root is resisted, the damage is resisted. That makes it a moderately resisted spell at level 39. At higher levels I can see it being used against MoBs that are highly magic resistant, but even then, it'll probably be resisted 30% of the time.<br>
It's a decent leading spell because of the 5 second cast time. It's almost worthless in combat solo. In groups it's ok.<br>
In PvP it's actually more useful. I was able to chain it on a warrior 5 times in a row. It only broke early once. If you need to keep someone rooted, and they have high magic resistance, this spell works very well.<br>
<br>
Overall, I give Elnerick's Entombment of Ice a C.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> O'Keils Embers</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
This is a great damage shield to have before we get our damage absorb skins. It's useful for when there are no mages/druids in the group. It's useful for helping out lower players. When used with our level 16 skin spell, it'll add even more damage when the mob starts whackin' on you.<br>
<br>
Overall, I give O'Keils Embers a C.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Nexus Gate/Portal/Translocate</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Since these spells are still nowhere to be found, I can only say what everybody else says. If they're only castable from Luclin, and all of our normal ports/trans will take us to the nexus instead of their normal destination, then why do we have a Nexus gate line?<br>
It would make more sense to make the nexus gates/portal castable from Norrath, since the Nexus is such a magnet on Luclin.<br>
The fact that these spells are still not found makes me think they weren't completely worked out before Luclin went live.<br>
<br>
Overall, I give Nexus Gate/Portal/Translocate a D.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Decession</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
While I haven't used Abscond to it's fullest capacity, I do know it has it's usefulness. Decession will allow me to integrate the same mode of travel to groupmates. This will save me alot of time for pre-raid prep, and for solo travel as duo groups as well.<br>
<br>
Overall, I give Decession a B.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Spellshield</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Well, from what I've read, this looks very valuble for raids against AoE MoBs. It absorbs up to 700 magical damage for 350 mana and a peridot. Oh, and it's supposed to be targetable. That means you can cast this on your Main puller to avoid them getting nuked to death on the pull.<br>
Add this to an enchanter rune, and you've got some serious shielding.<br>
In PvP this spell along with our epic's effect will make us extremely hard to nuke down.<br>
<br>
Overall, I give Spellshield a B.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Elnerick's Electrical Rending</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Well, after listening to Grimstaff say how useful big nukes would be, I became a believer. They do have their advantages in some situations. <br>
Before Luclin went live, this spell was cold based, but after some discussion, it was deemed more needed as a magical attack.<br>
1890 damage in 7.5 seconds for 525 mana = 3.6:1 ratio. Pretty good, a bit slow, but still very nice.<br>
PvP aspects: See below.<br>
<br>
Overall I give Elnerick's Electrical Rending a B.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Garrison's Superior Sundering</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The new grandadda of nukes, this one is our most damaging of all. 2100 damage in 8 seconds for 540 mana = 3.8:1 ratio. SLOW, but very high damage. No component either!<br>
In PvP these spells will allow wizards once shot kills, which I am absolutely against. These spells should be limited to 50% of their normal damage, or else Wizards will be WAY overpowered in PvP at 60.<br>
<br>
Overall I give Garrison's Superior Sundering a B.<br>
<br>
<br>
All in All, Luclin spells get a C+ from this player. They're better than average, but still lack in specific areas.<br>
